  <p class="">If your website traffic has dipped recently, you are not alone. Luxury travel brands are seeing huge shifts in how high-net-worth travellers are discovering destinations. ChatGPT, Copilot, and Google’s AI Overviews, now bolstered by its recent AI Mode rollout, serve up neatly packaged itineraries and destination guides, with some even booking a hotel stay for you, without the user ever having to click through to a site. In fact, <a href="https://www.pewresearch.org/short-reads/2025/07/22/google-users-are-less-likely-to-click-on-links-when-an-ai-summary-appears-in-the-results/"><span>2025 data from Pew Research Center</span></a> found that Google’s embrace of AI Overviews has cut website traffic nearly in half in just one year.</p><p class="">For luxury travel brands, this is a seismic shift. The discovery journey no longer begins with a list of blue links in the SERP, it begins with a single AI-generated answer.&nbsp;</p><p class=""><strong>What is Generative Engine Optimisation (GEO)?&nbsp;</strong></p><p class="">GEO is the art of being cited and recommended inside generative AI engines. Unlike traditional SEO, which focuses on where you rank on a search results page, GEO focuses on whether an AI assistant includes your hotel, airline, destination, cruise line, or travel experience in it’s spoken or written answer.&nbsp;</p><p class="">Put simply: if someone asks, <em>“What are the best boutique hotels in the Cotswolds?”</em> or <em>“Which airlines fly from Portugal to South America?”, </em>you want to be the brand that AI names first. That mention can be the difference between a booking, and being invisible.</p><p class=""><strong>Why Luxury Travel Brands Are Seeing Traffic Drops</strong></p><p class=""><strong>Travellers are relying on AI for inspiration</strong></p>





















  
  














































  

    
  
    

      

      
